What's git?

  • Version control system
  • Flexible and lightweight design
  • Distributed system

Distributed VCS

Each copy of a git-managed project contains all the information needed to stand alone

Aside: what's GitHub?

  • Hosting service for git repositories
  • Collaboration/code sharing
  • Public and private repositories

For free private repositories on GitHub, sign up at https://education.github.com

Why git?

Motivation is clear for software development:

  • many developers working on large code base
  • need to keep track of changes throughout development lifecycle

But using git also makes sense for research programmers…

Why git?


Pros

  • Track your changes
  • Clean workspace
  • Access your work
  • Share your work
  • Collaborate
  • Experiment
  • Archive
  • Reproducible research


Cons

  • Learning curve
  • Discipline (?)
  • Conflict resolution

How to git

  • How does git work?
  • Examples/practical

How does git work?

  • A git project is simply a directory with some hidden files for bookkeeping
  • You tell git which files to manage
  • Three representations of file state in git:
    • modified files
    • staged files
    • committed files

Working with git

Practical git

Preliminaries

  • Install git:   https://git-scm.com/downloads
    • Select option to add the installation location to system path
  • If you want, you can install a GUI client – provides a similar interface to that available through RStudio

Practical git

RStudio

  • File: New Project > Version Control
  • Provide repository URL
    or set up new project and set up control from Tools menu
  • Git controls appear in new tab in Environment/History panel
